<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-699-642  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 699 642.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Sept 25 1989 v23 n39 p25(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>PCs keep tabs on N.Y. students; record-keeping system easesplacement, frees teachers from paperwork.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pastore, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The New York public school system is automating its record-keepingand student tracking system.andP;  The project, called Automate theSchools is estimated at $88 million and will be fully implementedby 1992.andP;  Currently, 72 out of 924 schools are part of the system.andO;Software developed using Computer Corporation of America's Model204 data base management system runs in distributed mode on an IBM4381 at a central data center and on five IBM 9370s located ineach borough.andP;  The 9370s are linked to PS/2s in the individualschools.andP;  A T1 backbone wide-area network links all the computersover leased lines and an IBM Token-Ring network links themicrocomputers within each school.andP;  The system automates studentplacement, attendance records and state welfare-required reports,freeing administrators and teachers from time-consuming paperwork.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     New YorkEducational AdministrationRecords ManagementAutomationTracking SystemsWide Area Networks.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>